Prologue
"Please!" Queen Elwin pleaded, "Don't send her away! She's just a child!" The Ice King sat on his throne, looking down at his wife, with the royal advisor standing by. The queen had given birth to a daughter. Just thinking about it, the Ice King couldn't help but furrow his brow.
The baby girl looked very much like her mother: blue eyes, white hair, with a few strands of blue hair. The Ice King thought that having a daughter would make him look weak. After all, before this, he only had a son.
"You only have two choices: either kill the child or abandon her in the wilderness. Elwin, this is your punishment," she said bitterly, as if his name were poison. That was always how he was.
The Frostbound Realm is not always a kingdom. It once split into two parts, north and south. The north established a non-magical kingdom, while the south was a kingdom rich in fantasy power. Due to the greed of the north, an endless war erupted between the two kingdoms, until the south proposed a truce.
At that time, the southern region was already in despair, and the royal family was willing to do anything to prevent the bloody conflict. They proposed to marry their only princess to the north, making her queen of the north and giving birth to a son who would become the future king. After that, the south would merge with the north to establish a unified kingdom. The north accepted this proposal, and Princess Elwin was thus married to Prince Akur.
"Please, my king," Queen Elwin pleaded, hugging her child tightly, "for my child's safety, you can do anything to me—imprison me, exile me, even kill me."
The Ice King looked down at the queen, his eyes filled with disdain. Perhaps, just perhaps, he felt a little pity for her. After all, this woman had been by his side for 22 years, cared for him during his darkest moments, and bore him children.
"Alright. The child can live in the palace," said the Ice King. The queen sighed in relief. "But," he added, "you will be executed."
The royal advisors and Queen Elwen both showed expressions of fear. She slowly lowered her head, looking at the floor. "As you command, my king," she bowed.
The Ice King ordered the royal advisor to bring the queen's daughter to an empty room in Elwin. After that, he commanded the guards to take Elwin to the execution ground where all citizens could see.
When the guards led her to the execution ground, the citizens saw their only queen — also the kindest queen — about to be put to death, and they felt extremely angry. Some wept, others shouted and tried to attack the guards, while others wanted to know why such a thing was happening; yet they all shared the same question.
"Let her go!"
"Why did they treat her like that?"
When Alvin approached the wooden pillar, the most terrifying person in the kingdom appeared. He was the executioner of the pyre. The former queen Alvin was to be burned alive. No one should be subjected to the death by fire, even criminals. In the Frostborn realm, burning was the most cruel punishment.
Alvin was tied to a wooden post, and the king began to recount how the queen had betrayed them all. The people of the Frostspire Kingdom refused to believe, and would never accept the king's words. Then, the executioner lit the wooden post, and a single tear rolled down the face of the former queen.
"Carly, live on!" Thus ended the life of Queen Elwin.
The hall was completely silent.
In the southern wing of this cold palace, a ceaseless ticking sound echoes from the leftmost room. Former servants were always curious about what lay within, yet too afraid to approach. The maids moved about the hall, whispering and spreading all sorts of rumors. Some believed that the late Ice King's wife, Elwen, was confined in this room, waiting to be released.
They were completely wrong, Avery thought as she walked toward the South Wing. Servants walked along the walls, whispering to each other. They had no idea what was inside.
Of course, there are also many rumors about TA, because TA is the only person allowed to enter the room.
He knocked on the door. "Miss Carly, are you in there?" Avery whispered to the intricate door, adorned with snowflakes and crowns, symbols of royalty.
TA不知道这次她是否真的会让他进去，这和之前可不一样。我身上还有上次留下的淤青呢。艾弗里想起这件事，忍不住笑了出来。当时，卡莉把一本书扔向他，但当她看清是谁时，立刻道歉了。
A soft sound came from the room, as if saying she couldn't go anywhere, she was right there.
"Avery asked, 'May I come in?' TA couldn't forget the consequences of entering uninvited last time."
Another soft sound echoed in the room. It seemed to say, "Come in." A chill ran down Avery's spine, unsure whether it was from the cold or that voice. Although Avery had been there for many years, hearing the sound coming from the room still felt a bit strange.
"Avery stepped inside," she said, slowly opening the door. To a normal person, the scene in the room was quite unusual, but it wasn't unexpected. The room was filled with paper. Books were scattered around, the table was broken, and there were many ice sculptures scattered throughout. There were no windows, and there was almost no light. It was actually colder than any other part of the palace (which explained a lot). The room looked as if it had been hit by a blizzard, everything was in disarray.
The girl in the room was curled up in bed, wrapped in a blanket, reading from her notebook. A small lantern illuminated the room.
"Avery asked as she sat by Carly's bed, 'Which notebook are you reading?'"
